# diff

Compare two files (or trees) outside git — the tool for arbitrary files, where
@git/stage `diff` only covers tracked changes. `unified` is the patch-style
output `patch` and reviewers expect; `side` shows two columns; `dirs` walks two
directories; `ignorews` hides whitespace-only noise. The unified output is a
valid patch — redirect it to a `.patch` and apply with `patch -p1` or
`git apply`.

| Recipe | Flags | Shows |
|--------|-------|-------|
| `unified` | `-u` | patch-style, with `+`/`-` and context lines |
| `side` | `-y` | the two files in side-by-side columns |
| `dirs` | `-ru` | recursively compare two directories |
| `ignorews` | `-u -w` | unified, ignoring all whitespace differences |

Exit status is meaningful: `0` identical, `1` differ, `2` trouble — so
`diff -q a b` is a scriptable "are these the same?". `-r` recurses directories;
`-q` reports only *which* files differ (brief); `-w` ignores whitespace, `-i`
case. For a nicer rendering, pipe unified output through `delta` or use `git
diff --no-index a b`.

```just
# patch-style unified diff (default)
unified a b:
  diff -u -- {{quote(a)}} {{quote(b)}}

# side-by-side two-column comparison
side a b:
  diff -y -- {{quote(a)}} {{quote(b)}}

# recursively compare two directories
dirs a b:
  diff -ru -- {{quote(a)}} {{quote(b)}}

# unified diff ignoring all whitespace differences
ignorews a b:
  diff -u -w -- {{quote(a)}} {{quote(b)}}
```
